def build_model( reg_fn,
                name_y_col,
                name_x_cols,
                dataset,
                test_frac=0.3,
                preprocess_fn=None,
                show_plot_Y=False,
                show_plot_scatter=False):
    X=dataset[name_x_cols]
    Y=dataset[name_y_col]
    if preprocess_fn is not None:
        X=preprocess_fn(X)
    x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test= train_test_split(X,Y,test_size=test_frac)
    model=reg_fn(x_train,y_train)
    y_pred=model.predict(x_test)
    
    print("Training Score:",model.score(x_train,y_train))
    print("Testing Score:",R2(y_test,y_pred))
    
    if show_plot_Y==True:
        fix,ax= plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
        plt.plot(y_pred,label= "Predicted")
        plt.plot(y_test.values,label="Actual") #if values is removed...
        
        plt.ylabel(name_y_col)
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()
        
    if show_plot_scatter==True:
        fix,ax= plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
        plt.scatter(x_test,y_test)
        plt.plot(x_test,y_pred,'r') #if values is removed...
        
        plt.ylabel(name_of_y_col)
        plt.legend(["Predicted Line", "Observed Data"])
        plt.show()
        
    return{
        "training_score: ":model.score(x_train,y_train),
        "test_score: ": model.score(y_test,y_pred)
    }

Elastic net regression is a combination of Lasso regression and Ridge regression. If L1_ratio parameter=1 then it behaves is lasso regression...¶

Lasso: Regulates L1 norm parameters Ridge: Regulates L2 norm parameters...Check out the formulation for better understanding

# 2*elipson= range...all value under this is considered for regression line
# C= penalty to the points that lie epsilon tube while calc error...see notebook for more

def svr_reg(x_train, y_train, kernel='linear',epsilon=0.05, C=0.3):
    model=SVR(kernel=kernel,epsilon=epsilon,C=C)
    model.fit(x_train,y_train)
    return model

Polynomial Relation: If linear relation is not correct for data, there are two ways to tackle it. First way is to use polynomial equation to fit the data and thus create the boundary Second and perhaps handy way is to scale up the data by the correct order and then fit a linear model to it.
